{"body":"## Problem

Several failure paths in the run command only log warnings when `--verbose` is set. In normal usage, these failures are completely invisible to the user — they see success or unexpected behavior with no diagnostic information.

### Silent failure locations

**1. State reconciliation failure (run.ts:431-437)**
```typescript
} catch {
  if (config.verbose) {
    console.log(chalk.yellow(`  ⚠️  State reconciliation failed, continuing...`));
  }
}
```
If `.sequant/state.json` can't be reconciled (corruption, permission error), the user gets no feedback. Execution continues with potentially stale state.

**2. Metrics recording failure (run.ts:852-858)**
```typescript
} catch (metricsError) {
  if (config.verbose) {
    console.log(chalk.yellow(`  ⚠️  Metrics recording error: ${metricsError}`));
  }
}
```
Metrics silently fail. The user's `sequant stats` will show incomplete data with no explanation.

**3. State guard catch block (run.ts:463-466)**
```typescript
} catch {
  activeIssues.push(issueNumber);  // Silently includes issue on state lookup failure
}
```
If reading an issue's state throws (file corruption, race condition), the issue is silently added to the active list. Only verbose mode logs this.

### Why this matters

Users running `sequant run 123 456` in CI or in normal mode see clean output and assume everything worked. If state reconciliation failed, or metrics weren't recorded, they only discover it later when `sequant stats` is wrong or state is stale. The feedback loop is broken — they can't diagnose the problem without re-running with `--verbose`, by which point the transient error may not reproduce.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] State reconciliation failures log a one-line warning (yellow) in all modes, not just verbose
- [ ] Metrics recording failures log a one-line warning in all modes
- [ ] State guard catch blocks log which issue failed state lookup and why
- [ ] Verbose mode continues to show additional detail (stack trace, full error object) beyond the one-line warning
- [ ] No change to control flow — these are all non-fatal, execution still continues
- [ ] Existing tests pass; add test coverage for at least one of the warning paths

## Files in Scope

- `src/commands/run.ts` — lines 431-437, 463-466, 852-858

## Design Notes

The pattern should be:
```typescript
} catch (error) {
  console.log(chalk.yellow(`  ⚠️  State reconciliation failed, continuing...`));
  if (config.verbose) {
    console.log(chalk.gray(`    ${error}`));
  }
}
```

One-line summary always visible. Details in verbose. This is consistent with how other CLI tools (npm, git) handle non-fatal warnings.","labels":[{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACT-M2Rw","name":"bug","description":"Something isn't working","color":"d73a4a"},{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACVOX0xg","name":"cli","description":"CLI commands and interface","color":"5319E7"}],"state":"OPEN","title":"Surface error logging in non-verbose mode"}

